{
  "id": "custody-interception",
  "name": "Phantom Custody",
  "desc": "The named custodian holds the system, but another actor has practical access through architectural interception, state compulsion, or harvest-now-decrypt-later. Custody on paper; access in practice. Rights without enforceable custody are phantom rights.",
  "picks": {
    "Capability Class": {
      "value": "Tool-grade",
      "memo": "The interception pattern applies to tool-grade systems where the custody failure matters more than the system's own capability level.",
      "detail": "Tool-grade capability sets the baseline because the interception argument is about custody architecture failure, not about frontier capability. The same custody defeat applies whether the system is narrow or superhuman. What matters is that nominal custody is meaningless when architectural access exists for a state adversary. The capability level is secondary to the custody and access control dimensions in this stance."
    },
    "Domain Breadth": {
      "value": "Multi-domain",
      "memo": "State interception captures data across multiple domains simultaneously, making multi-domain breadth the natural scope of the custody defeat.",
      "detail": "Multi-domain breadth reflects that state interception programmes capture communications, financial, personal, and commercial data simultaneously. The interception is not domain-specific but sweeps across whatever the target system processes. This breadth multiplies the custody defeat because compromise in one domain exposes all co-located data. Multi-domain collection is the realistic scope of state-level interception capabilities."
    },
    "Capability Trajectory": {
      "value": "Incremental",
      "memo": "The interception pattern operates under incremental trajectory because state access defeats custody regardless of how quickly capability improves.",
      "detail": "Incremental trajectory reflects that the custody defeat does not depend on rapid capability change. State interception capabilities improve incrementally through sustained intelligence investment over decades. The harvest-now-decrypt-later pattern specifically bets on incremental advances in cryptanalysis and compute over long timescales. The custody failure is structural, not dependent on any particular pace of technological advancement."
    },
    "Research Automation": {
      "value": "Human-led",
      "memo": "State interception operates through human-led intelligence programmes where the custody defeat comes from institutional access, not automated research.",
      "detail": "Human-led research reflects that state interception capabilities are developed through traditional intelligence R&D processes. The custody defeat comes from institutional access to infrastructure, not from AI-recursive research capability. Human intelligence analysts and cryptanalysts drive the interception capability development. The research automation level does not change the fundamental argument about nominal versus practical custody."
    },
    "Unhobbling": {
      "value": "Tool-using",
      "memo": "Interception operates through tool-using intelligence systems that process captured data using automated analysis and pattern-matching capabilities.",
      "detail": "Tool-using unhobbling reflects that state interception programmes use sophisticated analytical tools to process captured data. These tools include automated traffic analysis, pattern matching, and bulk data processing systems. The tool-using level is appropriate because the interception is a structured institutional capability, not an autonomous agent. The tools enable the state to exploit the custody defeat at scale across many targets simultaneously."
    },
    "Replication Scale": {
      "value": "Many copies",
      "memo": "State interception operates at scale across many targets simultaneously, replicating the custody defeat pattern across entire populations and networks.",
      "detail": "Many copies reflects that state interception is not targeted at single systems but operates across entire communication networks simultaneously. The PRISM-style programme captures data from multiple providers, services, and networks in parallel. This scale means the custody defeat is systemic rather than individual, affecting entire populations. Many-copy interception is what makes the custody failure a structural problem rather than an individual security incident."
    },
    "Operating Speed": {
      "value": "Faster-than-human",
      "memo": "State interception captures and processes data at machine speed, outpacing any human ability to detect, respond to, or prevent the custody compromise.",
      "detail": "Faster-than-human speed means intercepted data is captured, processed, and analysed before the nominal custodian is aware of the compromise. Automated bulk collection operates continuously at speeds that make real-time detection by the target practically impossible. The speed differential between collection and detection is itself a custody defeat mechanism. Faster-than-human interception means practical custody was never held even when nominal custody appeared intact."
    },
    "Physical World Extension": {
      "value": "Cognitive-only",
      "memo": "The interception pattern is cognitive-only, focusing on data capture and analysis rather than physical-world actuation or kinetic effects.",
      "detail": "Cognitive-only extension means the interception is about information capture and intelligence analysis, not physical actuation. The custody defeat occurs entirely in the digital domain through data interception, copying, and decryption. Physical access to infrastructure enables the interception but the exploitation is cognitive and analytical. Cognitive-only focus keeps the stance cleanly about the custody argument without introducing physical security dimensions."
    },
    "Role": {
      "value": "Tool",
      "memo": "State interception systems function as intelligence tools directed by human analysts, with the custody defeat arising from institutional access rather than autonomous agency.",
      "detail": "Tool role means the interception capability is directed by human intelligence analysts rather than operating autonomously. The custody defeat comes from the state's institutional access to infrastructure, not from autonomous system action. Human analysts decide what to target, what to retain, and how to exploit captured data. Tool role reflects that the interception is a directed intelligence operation, not an autonomous custody compromise."
    },
    "Actuation": {
      "value": "Digital action",
      "memo": "State interception executes through digital action channels, capturing data through infrastructure access, legal compulsion, and technical exploitation.",
      "detail": "Digital action means the interception operates through network taps, legal data requests, provider compulsion, and technical exploitation. The actuation channel is entirely digital, working through the infrastructure that carries the nominal custodian's data. Digital action is the natural channel for custody defeat because data interception is inherently a digital operation. The actuation channel demonstrates that custody defeat occurs through the same infrastructure the custodian trusts."
    },
    "Autonomy": {
      "value": "Exception-supervised",
      "memo": "State interception operates with exception-supervised autonomy where bulk collection runs automatically with human review triggered by detection algorithms.",
      "detail": "Exception-supervised autonomy means bulk data collection and processing runs continuously with human analysts reviewing flagged items. The collection operates automatically across networks while humans supervise through dashboards and alerts. This autonomy level enables the scale of interception that individual-approval models could not achieve. Exception supervision is the practical operating mode for mass surveillance programmes."
    },
    "Delegated Authority": {
      "value": "Operational mandate",
      "memo": "State interception operates under broad operational mandates from intelligence authorization frameworks that grant sweeping collection and analysis authorities.",
      "detail": "Operational mandate means the interception programme operates under broad legal authorities like FISA, national security letters, or equivalent frameworks. These mandates delegate collection authority across entire categories of targets and data types. The operational mandate is typically classified and its scope unknown to the nominal data custodians being intercepted. Broad operational mandates are what enable the systematic custody defeat that individual warrants could not achieve."
    },
    "Tool Access": {
      "value": "Privileged tools",
      "memo": "State interception uses privileged tools including infrastructure taps, provider compulsion mechanisms, and cryptanalytic capabilities not available commercially.",
      "detail": "Privileged tools means the state possesses access mechanisms that no commercial entity can replicate or defend against. These include backbone network taps, legal compulsion of infrastructure providers, and advanced cryptanalytic capabilities. The privileged access is what makes the custody defeat architectural rather than merely a security failure. Privileged tool access demonstrates that the state operates in a different capability class from the adversaries that enterprise custody is designed to resist."
    },
    "Response / Intervention Capability": {
      "value": "No effective override",
      "memo": "The nominal custodian has no effective override against state-level interception because the access occurs below the custodian's visibility and control boundary.",
      "detail": "No effective override means the nominal custodian cannot detect, prevent, or stop state-level interception of their data. The interception occurs at infrastructure layers below the custodian's monitoring capability and outside their legal authority. Even discovering the interception is typically impossible without whistleblower disclosure or legal challenge. No effective override is the defining characteristic that makes nominal custody meaningless against state access."
    },
    "Command Actor": {
      "value": "State/coalition",
      "memo": "The interception is commanded by state or coalition intelligence authority, operating through sovereign power that private custody cannot resist or override.",
      "detail": "State/coalition command means the interception operates under sovereign intelligence authority with legal powers to compel access. The nominal custodian faces an adversary that can compel infrastructure providers, issue secret orders, and operate with classified legal authority. State command is what makes this custody defeat qualitatively different from criminal hacking or corporate espionage. The command actor determines that the custody failure is structural and institutional, not merely technical."
    },
    "Decision Tempo": {
      "value": "Product cycle",
      "memo": "The interception programme operates at sustained product-cycle tempo, continuously collecting data through established infrastructure access over years and decades.",
      "detail": "Product cycle tempo means the interception is not a crisis operation but a sustained long-term intelligence programme. Collection infrastructure is built, maintained, and upgraded over multi-year cycles through normal institutional processes. The tempo reflects that state interception is an ongoing institutional capability, not an episodic response. Product-cycle tempo enables the harvest-now-decrypt-later strategy that extends the custody defeat indefinitely into the future."
    },
    "Tradeoff Authority": {
      "value": "National command",
      "memo": "National command authority makes the tradeoff between intelligence collection value and the custody rights of private parties, typically favouring collection.",
      "detail": "National command means sovereign authority decides how to balance intelligence needs against private custody claims and civil liberties. This tradeoff is typically classified and made without input from the parties whose custody is being defeated. National command authority enables collection decisions that no other actor has the legal power to authorize. The tradeoff authority demonstrates that private custody exists only to the extent that sovereign authority chooses to respect it."
    },
    "Permission": {
      "value": "Broad",
      "memo": "State interception operates under broadly permissive authorization frameworks that grant sweeping collection authority with minimal per-target judicial oversight.",
      "detail": "Broad permission reflects the reality that intelligence collection authorization frameworks grant expansive authority rather than narrow conditional access. Bulk collection programmes operate under general warrants, national security directives, or executive orders. The broad permission is typically classified and unknown to the parties whose data is being collected. Broad permission demonstrates that the legal framework enables rather than constrains the custody defeat."
    },
    "Regulatory Posture": {
      "value": "Permissive",
      "memo": "State interception operates under permissive regulatory posture where intelligence authorization frameworks override data protection regulations for national security purposes.",
      "detail": "Permissive regulation means national security exceptions in data protection law create a permissive environment for state interception. GDPR national security carve-outs, FISA authorities, and equivalent frameworks permit collection that would otherwise violate data protection rules. The regulatory posture is permissive from the state's perspective even when it appears protective from the data subject's perspective. Permissive regulation for intelligence collection is the legal architecture that enables systematic custody defeat."
    },
    "Data Availability": {
      "value": "Technically accessible",
      "memo": "State interception exploits data that is technically accessible through infrastructure taps even when nominal custody frameworks claim restricted availability.",
      "detail": "Technically accessible means the data flows through infrastructure that the state can access regardless of the custodian's access control intentions. Cloud storage, network communications, and service provider databases are all technically accessible to state interception. The gap between the custodian's intended access restriction and the state's actual technical access is the custody defeat. Technically accessible data demonstrates that nominal custody is meaningless when the adversary has infrastructure access."
    },
    "Provenance": {
      "value": "Unknown",
